Sentencas: Phosphine (PH3) as a contaminant in coal syngas has been shown to cause permanent degradation on solid oxide fuel cell (SOFC) anode performance.
Titulo: The effect of overpotential on performance degradation of the solid oxide fuel cell Ni/YSZ anode during exposure to syngas with phosphine contaminant

Sentencas: Previous studies on the performance degradation have been performed at constant current or constant voltage over the entire experiment.
Titulo: The effect of overpotential on performance degradation of the solid oxide fuel cell Ni/YSZ anode during exposure to syngas with phosphine contaminant

Sentencas: In this work, the effect of overpotential (difference between the open circuit voltage and the applied voltage) on rates of degradation of SOFC performance is examined.
Titulo: The effect of overpotential on performance degradation of the solid oxide fuel cell Ni/YSZ anode during exposure to syngas with phosphine contaminant

Sentencas: A commercial SOFC from MSRI is exposed in sequence to first hydrogen, then coal syngas and then coal syngas with 10 ppm PH3.
Titulo: The effect of overpotential on performance degradation of the solid oxide fuel cell Ni/YSZ anode during exposure to syngas with phosphine contaminant

Sentencas: The rates of cell power density loss rates are monitored for three overpotentials (0.1, 0.2 and 0.3 V).
Titulo: The effect of overpotential on performance degradation of the solid oxide fuel cell Ni/YSZ anode during exposure to syngas with phosphine contaminant

Sentencas: There is no apparent correlation between the degradation rates and overpotential values.
Titulo: The effect of overpotential on performance degradation of the solid oxide fuel cell Ni/YSZ anode during exposure to syngas with phosphine contaminant

Sentencas: Post-mortem studies including SEM, XRD and XPS confirm the migration of nickel to the anode surface and the formation of a nickel phosphide phase.
Titulo: The effect of overpotential on performance degradation of the solid oxide fuel cell Ni/YSZ anode during exposure to syngas with phosphine contaminant
